## Problem Statement

One of the great things I've realized through our MSDS journey is not only the ability to ask the right questions and maximize the business value of the problems we solve, but also the ability to incorporate our learnings to our hobbies and passion. For this study, we aim to apply the learnings from Machine Learning 2.0 class to one of my passions, music.

Recurrent Neural Network (`RNN`) are networks that are used for "things" that happen recurrently, for example, time series. But, RNN can also be used as a generative model, meaning, in addition to being used as a predictive model, it can learn the sequences of a problem and then generate entirely new plausible sequences for the problem domain.

Long Short-Term Memory networks (`LSTM`) are a specific type of recurrent neural networks that are capable of learning the relationships between elements in an input sequence. It is especially equipped to handle longer distance dependencies including ones you get with language. Hence, LSTM has been one of the famous architectures widely used in Natural Language Processing (`NLP`).

In this study, we explore usage of LSTM as a text generator, but more importantly in a different language than English, which is `Filipino`. More specifically, we aim to explore the work of 
<a href="https://jeppbautista.wordpress.com/portfolio/creating-opm-songs-using-deep-learning/">Jepp Bautista</a> 
in using LSTM to train on Original Pilipino Music (`OPM`) lyrics by various Filipino bands and singers and generate new lyrics for a melody I have created almost 3 years ago to produce a new original OPM song.

## Methodology

### 1. Data description and collection
The data used in this study is from <a href="https://genius.com/">Genius.com</a>, one of the famous websites that displays lyrics to every song possible, including songs from OPM artists. Data is composed of lyrics from the most famous artists and bands in the Philippines such as, Kamikazee, Parokya ni Edgar, Callalily, December Avenue, Silent Sanctuary, Moira dela Torre, Jireh Lim, This band, Ben&Ben and I belong to the zoo.

<img src="https://github.com/jeddahlyngacera/opm-text-gen-lstm/blob/master/img1.PNG">

### 2. Data preparation and processing
All lyrics are appended to one text file `opm-lyrics.txt` to be used as training set for the LSTM model.

**2.1 Load needed libraries**


```python
import numpy as np
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, Dense, Dropout, LSTM
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint, ReduceLROnPlateau, EarlyStopping, ModelCheckpoint
from tensorflow.python.keras import utils
```

**2.2 Load train data and convert to lowercase**


```python
raw_text = open('opm-lyrics.txt').read()
raw_text = raw_text.lower()
```

**2.3 Create mapping of unique chars to integers**


```python
chars = sorted(list(set(raw_text)))
char_to_int = dict((c, i) for i, c in enumerate(chars))
int_to_char = dict((i, c) for i, c in enumerate(chars))
```


```python
n_chars = len(raw_text)
n_vocab = len(chars)
print('Total Characters:', n_chars)
print('Total Vocab:', n_vocab)
```

    Total Characters: 28056
    Total Vocab: 32
    

**2.4 Prepare the dataset of input to output pairs encoded as integers**


```python
seq_length = 80
dataX = []
dataY = []
for i in range(0, n_chars - seq_length, 1):
    seq_in = raw_text[i: i + seq_length]
    seq_out = raw_text[i + seq_length]
    dataX.append([char_to_int[char] for char in seq_in])
    dataY.append(char_to_int[seq_out])
```


```python
n_patterns = len(dataX)
print('Total Patterns:', n_patterns)
```

    Total Patterns: 27976
    

**2.5 Reshape X to be `[samples, time steps, features]` and normalize**


```python
X = np.reshape(dataX, (n_patterns, seq_length, 1)) / float(n_vocab)
```

**2.6 One hot encode the output variable**


```python
y = utils.to_categorical(dataY)
```

Data is now ready for modeling into LSTM.

### 3. Modeling
Original study made by <a href="https://jeppbautista.wordpress.com/portfolio/creating-opm-songs-using-deep-learning/">Jepp Bautista</a> used the following architecture:


```python
model = Sequential()
model.add(LSTM(512, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(X.shape[1], X.shape[2])))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))
model.add(LSTM(256, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(y.shape[1], activation='softmax'))
model.summary()
```

For this study, we have explored the following cases:
* increase LSTM layers
* additional dropouts
* varying the number of units
* varying the dropout percentage
The architecture of the final model used is displayed in the next section.

**3.1 Define LSTM model**


```python
model = Sequential()
model.add(LSTM(512, return_sequences=True, input_shape=(X.shape[1], X.shape[2])))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))
model.add(LSTM(256, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(LSTM(128))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(y.shape[1], activation='softmax'))
model.summary()
```

```python
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics = ['accuracy'])
```

**3.2 Define callbacks list**


```python
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(filepath='best_weights.hdf5', monitor='loss', save_best_only=True, save_weights_only=True)
lr_reduce = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='loss', factor=0.2, patience=2, verbose=2, mode='max')
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='loss', min_delta=0.005, patience=2, verbose=2, mode='min')

callbacks_list = [checkpoint, lr_reduce, early_stop]
```

**3.3 Train model**

Note that for simplicity, only 5 epochs are shown below:


```python
model.fit(X, y, epochs=5, batch_size=32, verbose=1, callbacks=callbacks_list);
```

**3.4 Load model with best weight**

After modeling for at least 100 epochs (fitting is incremental so code above was just rerun to improve model up until the alloted time), we load the best weight saved to the file defined above `best_weights.hdf5` and use it to generate text.


```python
model.load_weights('best_weights.hdf5')
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics = ['accuracy'])
```

**3.5 Generate text**


```python
def generate_text(dataX):
    start = np.random.randint(0, len(dataX)-1)
    pattern = dataX[start]
    print('Seed:\n' + '\"', ''.join([int_to_char[value] for value in pattern]) + '\"')
    output = []
    for i in range(350):
        x = np.reshape(pattern, (1, len(pattern), 1)) / float(n_vocab)
        prediction = model.predict(x, verbose=0)
        index = np.argmax(prediction)
        result = int_to_char[index]
        output.append(result)
        pattern.append(index)
        pattern = pattern[1:len(pattern)]
    return ''.join(output)
```


```python
pred1 = generate_text(dataX)
```

## Results and discussion

Text generated from the multi-layered LSTM model have phrases that make sense and can be used as lyrics to songs. Although, a lot of it are just direct copies from the lyrics or words that don't make sense. To solve this, it is recommended to explore more variants of the architecture, or add other deep learning models or variations of RNN. Training on a much larger corpus will also improve the learning of the model.

However, our model was able to provide `59 usable phrases` that we can use as lyrics to the melody I created. These phrases can help me with writer's block and give me an idea of the `current themes of OPM`. We can use the phrases as `inspiration` to create the lyric that would suit our melody.

## Summary/Main learning points

`Text generation` using recurrent neural networks such as LSTM can be used in almost if not all `languages` as it learns the sequences of the input regardless of the content, e.g., Filipino language, as shown in this study.

`Deep learning is an art`. We have made this our cohort's mantra because there is really no exact guideline on how to create the best architecture for our deep learning models. What we only know are the options we have to improve them, such as, playing with the kind of layers, how many of them, number of units, percentages, number of executions, etc.

In the future, I plan to explore `intervening` on the outputs of the model by forcing it to choose on words that `rhyme` together, as suggested by Prof. Chris Monterola. Note that rhyming in Filipino is interestingly different from the English language. This way, we will be able to create a model that will produce lyrics or poems that we can use on its entirety and not just to be used as inspiration.

Also, I will be trying to implement this study's method on other languages that I can speak, `Spanish and Korean`, and see the differences of the outputs generated. It is especially interesting to see the results on Korean as its words are grouped by syllables, and not on letters.
